ion. Drawing on two decades of ethnographic research across the Middle East with hundreds of men from a variety of social and religious backgrounds, Marcia Inhorn shows how the new Arab man is self-consciously rethinking the patriarchal masculinity of his forefathers and unseating received wisdoms. This is especially true in childless Middle Eastern marriages where, contrary to popular belief, infertility is more common among men than women. Inhorn captures the marital, moral, and material commitments of couples undergoing assisted reproduction, revealing how new technologies are transforming their lives and religious sensibilities. And she looks at the changing manhood of husbands who undertake transnational "egg quests"--set against the backdrop of war and economic uncertainty--out of devotion to the infertile wives they love. Trenchant and emotionally gripping, The New Arab Man traces the emergence of new masculinities in the Middle East in the era of biotechnology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAnthropology. 0aFertilization in vitro, Human. 0aGender Studies. 0aInfertilityvMiddle EastvPsychological aspects. 0aInfertilityzMiddle EastxPsychological aspects. 0aIslamic Studies. 0aMan-woman relationshipsvMiddle East. 0aMan-woman relationshipszMiddle East. 0aMasculinityvMiddle East. 0aMasculinityvReligious aspectsvIslam. 0aMasculinityxReligious aspectsxIslam. 0aMasculinityzMiddle East. 0aMenvMiddle East. 0aMenzMiddle East. 0aPSYCHOLOGYvEthnopsychology. 0aSOCIAL SCIENCEvMen's Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aAmerica.  aArab countries.  aArab men.  aDNA analysis.  aEgyptian masculinity.  aIVF community.  aIVF settings.  aIslam.  aIslamophobia.  aMarxist sociology.  aMiddle East.  aMiddle Eastern conjugality.  a